Save the Date! On Tuesday, March 10, David Bolt, Founder and Director of the Sustainable Future Center, will join us here in Fourth and Gill to speak on sustainable practices in our urban gardens. David was selected as a White House “Champion of Change in Corporate Environmental Sustainability” in 2012. That award recognized the central theme of David’s life and his career. He has long sought to eliminate waste, promote efficiency, and preserve the world for future generations.
 
The talk is sponsored by Fourth and Gill’s own “Gillbilly Garden Club”. Thanks to Jamey Dobbs who helped arrange for our speaker.  Please come and invite others who might be interested.

Place: Central Methodist Church (2nd floor meeting room)

—-
David,
 
    I spoke at length today with Cliff Honicker who is a grant writer – but mostly is a farmer!  Cliff and his wife – who is a lawyer – have about 120 acres near the Grainger County line.  He says he’s not fully organic, but is practicing a lot of very interesting and ecologically sound techniques.  Better still, when I mentioned hugelkultur, he knew exactly what I was talking about and, in fact, taught me a couple of things about it. 
 
    In short, he’s very interested in what we’re trying to do and certainly wants to help.  I sent him a note with a general description of what we’re doing, and I included a copy of the current draft of the plan.  I also sent him some links to Permaculture sites and Geoff’s site to help bring him up to speed on that. 
 
    Unfortunately Cliff is having to split his time between here and Houston to deal with a very ill sister.  About the earliest I can get to sit down with him will probably be the week of October 20th – and only if I’m not in surgery that week.  In any case, he’s interested, and he’s knowledgeable which is all good.
 
    Jim

Mary,

You are correct, chicken "poop" is a valuable resource that should not be wasted.  It is very hot and cannot be used directly on plants but it can be used as a very rich nitrogen source for compost.  If you get tired of scooping there are less labor intensive ways of keeping the coop clean.

I would suggest you come one Saturday and see our coop setup and Amy or myself can talk about options.  Any time from 9:00 to 12:00 would be good.


You David Bolt
Interim Executive Director / Founder
Sustainable Future Center

865-294-0154 Office

Message: Hello! 
We just got 5 chickens in April,  they are just now starting to lay. So we have since switched to sand and scooping it everyday which the girls seem to like better......I don't want to waste all this nitrogen rich poop so we would love to compost but I don't know the first thing about safely/effectively composting.... Do you have any classes/resources to learn how to do this?  Thanks so much!!
